author_association":"OWNER","active_lock_reason":null,"body":"The point of this issue is to start a discussion on the matter of moving from using Jinja2 and Flask for Maniwani's frontend to one of React or Vue, the reason being that stuff like the live updating code requires duplication of template knowledge; posts are always rendered server-side, so as it stands the process for dynamically adding a new post looks something like this:\r\n* Send post information back to server to be rendered there.\r\n* Retrieve rendered HTML from server and render it on the client.\r\nDynamically-added new replies follow a similar process, but must duplicate some HTML templating since the server doesn't currently render replies for individual posts. It's all very ugly, and really needs to be streamlined.\r\n\r\nMigrating the Jinja templates over to React/Vue would significantly streamline the whole process, as templates would be only stored once, and no information would need to be duplicated. To support clients who don't have Javascript enabled, the templates can be rendered server-side before sending the rendered result plus Javascript over the pipe.\r\n\r\nThe primary drawback of this approach is twofold, as I see it:\r\n* The JS templates will need access to internal structures that ordinary API clients should not have access to (configuration, etc.) - in other words, there will need to be an internal backend API secured from access by the outside.\r\n* Introducing JS-backed SSR will add another moving part into the mix, namely, a Node server running alongside Flask. While Docker can hide this somewhat, administratiors opting to take the non-Docker route will have to install and maintain Node in addition to the other Python dependencies. That said, Node is already a buildtime requirement, so it might not be too bad.","performed_via_github_app":null,"score":1.0},{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Swizz/hyperapp-html/issues/18","repository_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Swiz